Density Estimation

Ryan Miller

Introduction

  • In statistics, we often adopt the notion that data arises from some sort of underlying distribution
  • A density function describes the relative frequencies of certain values of a variable
    • All density functions must integrate to 1, so the area under the density curve of \(X\) between points \(a\) and \(a\) determines the probability that we see a data-point having an \(X\) value between \(a\) and \(b\)
    • The normal curve, defined mathetmatically by \(f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}}e^{-\frac{(x - \mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}}\), is an example of a density function
    • The figure below illustrates a familiar feature of the standard normal density

Why Worry About Densities?

  • Below is a rugplot of a variable \(X\), which shows every individual data-point, and a histogram, which aggregates the data to display relative frequencies (ie: the histograms estimates the density function of \(X\))
    • Which do you think is more useful in understanding \(X\)?

Histograms and Density Estimation

  • Whenever we are interested the relative frequencies of a variable, we should consider estimating its density function
  • Histograms provide a coarse method of density estimation
    • In this example, \(X\) consists of \(n=100\) draws from the standard normal distribution
    • Notice the histogram of \(X\) only vaguely resembles the underlying normal curve (shown in red)
  • Can we do better?

Kernel Density Estimation

  • Histograms divide the data into buckets, treating all data-points with a bucket as equal
    • This means data-points near the boundaries of a bucket contribute just as much as those near the midpoint
    • The result is a jagged density estimate that is highly sensitive to how the buckets are defined
  • Alternatively, Kernel density estimation (KDE) takes a point-by-point approach to density estimation
    • Before explaining the method, let’s first see a density estimate that KDE produces (shown in blue)

Kernel Density Estimation

  • In our example, the kernel density estimate is a much more accurate representation of the underlying density of \(X\) than the histogram
  • KDE works by giving each datapoint a kernel (most often a normal density), these kernels are then aggregated (weighting each by \(1/n\) and then “stacking”) to produce an overall density estimate

Bandwidth

  • It is natural for the mean (center) of each data-point’s kernel to be the value of the datapoint itself
  • The standard deviation (spread) of the normal kernel is something the analyst must decide
    • This standard deviation is known as bandwidth
    • Bandwidth governs how smooth a kernel density estimate is, in ggplot it is controlled by the bw argument in geom_density()

Other Kernels

  • Normal kernels are usually a reasonable choice, but there are other possibilities such as rectangles or triangles
    • The shape of these kernels is particularly noticeable in the low density region near -2
    • The type of kernel can be changed using the kernel argument in geom_density(), for example kernel = "rectangular"

KDE in Two-Dimensions

  • Kernel density estimation is a flexible method that easily extends to two-dimensions
    • In the example shown below, the argument h = c(15,25) sets the bandwidths for the \(X\) and \(Y\) dimensions respectively
    • The scale level refers to the “height” of the density estimate at given x-y coordinate
set.seed(11)
xx <- rnorm(200, mean = 3, sd = .7)
yy <- rnorm(200, mean = 5, sd = 1.7)
df <- data.frame(x = xx, y = yy)

ggplot(df, aes(x = x, y = y)) + stat_density_2d(aes(fill = stat(level)), geom = "polygon", color = "white", h = c(2,2))

Example - Diabetes Among Pima Indians

  • The graphs below show the blood glucose measurements of 736 Pima Indians following a glucose tolerance test
  • Based upon the histograms, it looks most diabetics had higher blood glucose measurements than non-diabetics
    • But these data are noisy, and the different numbers of diabetics/non-diabetics complicates the comparison
    • In contrast, KDE clearly clearly shows the relative likelihood of diabetes is much higher at high blood glucose levels

Example - Diabetes Among Pima Indians

  • We can also compare the relative frequencies of diabetics and non-diabetics in two-dimensions
    • Diabetics tend to have both higher mass and higher glucose

Example - Diamond Prices

  • Even with transparency of alpha = .1, it is hard to judge the relative concentrations of data-points in the scatterplot

Takeaways

  • Kernel density estimation is a useful strategy for representing the distribution of numeric variables
  • For large datasets, density estimates can be easier to interpret than scatterplots or rugplots
